            actLabel: "Opening",
            contentBlocks: "[{\"type\": \"context\", \"label\": \"Scene Setup\", \"content\": \"Open with the audience grounded in the specific, painful reality of wealth management IT. This is not a generic ITSM story \\u2014 it is a story about trading platforms going dark during market hours, Bloomberg terminal connectivity dropping at market close, regulatory reporting systems failing before SEC filing deadlines, and compliance workflows stalling while auditors wait. The business impact of IT downtime here is measured in dollars per minute of trading disruption, regulatory fines, and client churn from institutional accounts. The audience \\u2014 a mix of C-suite and practitioners \\u2014 will immediately recognize these stakes. Your job in the opening is to make them feel the problem before you show the solution. Do not demo anything yet. Set the scene with data, empathy, and a clear 'before and after' framing.\"}, {\"type\": \"note\", \"label\": \"Pre-Demo Setup\", \"content\": \"No instance navigation required for the opening. Prepare a single slide or whiteboard visual (optional) showing a notional incident timeline: 08:47 \\u2014 Bloomberg market data feed fails; 08:49 \\u2014 analyst opens incident; 09:22 \\u2014 root cause identified; 09:41 \\u2014 resolution deployed. Highlight that 54 minutes of degraded trading capability cost the firm an estimated $2.1M in missed execution windows. Alternatively, open on the ServiceNow homepage with the Employee Center visible but not in focus \\u2014 this creates a natural visual anchor for the transition into Act 1.\"}, {\"type\": \"actions\", \"label\": \"Click-by-Click\", \"items\": [\"No clicks required during the opening. Keep the screen on a neutral landing page \\u2014 the ServiceNow homepage or the Employee Center portal landing page (https://[instance].service-now.com/esc) \\u2014 so the audience orients to the platform without distraction.\", \"Optional: if you want a visual anchor, navigate to All > Incident > Open Incidents and leave the list visible in the background. Do not click into any incident yet.\", \"The opening is entirely verbal and narrative. Reserve all interaction for Act 1.\"]}, {\"type\": \"talktrack\", \"label\": \"Talk Track\", \"content\": \"Open with a grounded, empathetic statement about the wealth management operating environment. Do not lead with product features.\", \"lines\": [{\"persona\": \"You\", \"text\": \"Let me start by talking about a morning that every one of you has probably lived through. It is 8:47 AM Eastern. Markets open in 43 minutes. Your Bloomberg market data feed connectivity service goes down \\u2014 silently. No alert. No automated page. A trader notices prices are not updating and calls the help desk. By the time your Level 2 analyst has read through the last five incident notes, checked the runbook on the shared drive, looped in the network team, and written the first update \\u2014 it is 9:22. Thirty-five minutes of degraded trading capability. In a firm managing $40 billion in AUM, that window matters.\"}, {\"persona\": \"You\", \"text\": \"Now multiply that across every Bloomberg terminal incident, every portfolio management system outage, every compliance workflow failure in the 72 hours before a regulatory filing. That is the reality your service desk is living in today. And the answer most firms reach for is more headcount. More analysts. More on-call rotations. But the volume is growing faster than you can hire.\"}, {\"persona\": \"Victoria Chen\", \"text\": \"That timeline is painfully accurate. Our MTTR on trading platform incidents is just over four hours. Every time it spikes, I get a call from the Head of Trading.\"}, {\"persona\": \"You\", \"text\": \"That is exactly the problem we are solving today. What we are going to show you is how Now Assist \\u2014 ServiceNow's generative AI layer built natively into the platform \\u2014 compresses that four-hour timeline at every stage: the moment an employee searches for help, the moment an analyst opens the incident, the moment knowledge needs to be captured, and the moment an AI Agent can resolve the issue entirely without human intervention. Let me show you what that looks like.\"}]}, {\"type\": \"watchfor\", \"label\": \"Watch For\", \"items\": [\"Read the room \\u2014 if the C-suite audience is nodding, you have the right level of specificity. If they look distracted, sharpen the dollar figure or name a specific platform (Bloomberg, Fidessa, Charles River) they recognize.\", \"The practitioner in the room (Marcus persona) may visibly react to the 'copy-pasting between systems' description \\u2014 use that energy to validate the problem.\", \"Keep the opening under 5 minutes. The temptation is to over-explain. Trust the narrative and move to Act 1 promptly.\"]}, {\"type\": \"caution\", \"label\": \"Caution\", \"content\": \"Do not name specific client firms or cite real regulatory fines without clearing them with your customer success team. Use notional figures ('a firm of your scale,' 'estimated $X per minute'). Avoid leading with product feature names like 'Now Assist' or 'Agentic AI' in the opening \\u2014 lead with business pain, not capabilities. Save the product vocabulary for when you demonstrate it.\"}, {\"type\": \"transition\", \"label\": \"Transition to Act 1\", \"content\": \"The first place AI can intervene is before a ticket is ever created. Your employees are already searching for answers \\u2014 they just are not finding them fast enough. Let me show you what AI-powered search looks like for a wealth management analyst trying to resolve a Bloomberg connectivity issue on their own.\"}, {\"type\": \"painpoints\", \"label\": \"Pain Points Addressed\", \"items\": [\"Victoria Chen: High MTTR on trading platform incidents driving revenue loss and executive escalations\", \"Marcus Rivera: Time lost reading incident history and hunting for resolution steps across disconnected systems\", \"Jordan Patel: Difficulty quantifying AI value to leadership \\u2014 opening establishes the baseline that Act 1\\u20134 will improve against\"]}]",
